\subparagraph{Page Break}\label{page-break-4}

\section{Discussion}\label{discussion}

\subsection{Fisheries and stock
status}\label{fisheries-and-stock-status}

As the data from the fisheries itself does not yet allow for a
comprehensive assessment of the stock size and fishing status, these
properties must be estimated from other sources. For the pelagic species
which make up the majority of the catch, it can be assumed that no
separate Jordanian population exists and that they are part of the
broader Red Sea stock. Additionally, the swordfish caught in Jordan are
most likely part of the Indian Ocean stock. The Indian Ocean swordfish
is currently not overfished, and the biomass is close to the maximum
sustainable yield threshold (BMSY).

According to earlier investigations, the tuna catch mostly consists of
three species. The most common are the Skipjack (\emph{Katsuwonis
pelamis}) and the Kawakawa (\emph{Euthynnus affinis}). Minor catches
consist of Yellowfin tuna (\emph{Thunnus albacares}), Dogtooth tuna
(\emph{Gymnosarda unicolor}) and Longtail tuna (\emph{Thunnus tonggol})
(Al-Zibdeh 2007). All of the tuna are taken from a larger migrating
population, of which only a small part migrates to Jordan. The sardines
and mackerels, which form another important component of the catch, are
also most likely part of a bigger population in the Red Sea and not a
local fish stock. Separate stock assessments for these species in the
Red Sea do not yet exist.

In contrast to the most important commercially fished species, which are
migratory and pelagic, the reef fish species which make only a small
part of the landings are local populations. Although the gathered data
does not yet allow for an estimation of stock size and fishing status,
first conclusions can be drawn from ReefCheck Surveys, carried out by
the Aqaba Marine Park during the PERSGA project in 2008 and by JREDS in
2015. These surveys focus on indicator species to give a rough
estimation of important reef fish populations.

The snapper was selected as an indicator species because of its
importance as a culinary fish that is caught by nets near reefs. Average
snapper abundance for the whole region was 22.4A±19.34 fish per 100
m\textsuperscript{2} reef, but no snappers were found in Jordan in 2006,
2008 (PERSGA 2010) and 2015 (JREDS 2015).

Parrotfish were selected as an indicator of over-fishing of various
kinds. Between 1.25 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2} reef (PERSGA 2010)
and 1.8 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2} reef (JREDS 2015) were found in
surveys of the area. This is lower than in Egypt (2.13 fish per
100m\textsuperscript{2} reef) and Saudi Arabia (2.24 fish per
100m\textsuperscript{2} reef) (PERSGA 2010).

Butterflyfish of the family Chaetodontidae are taken as indicators for
over-fishing (they are often bycatch in reef fisheries), ornamental fish
trade and reef health. In Jordan, around 6.88A±1.24 fish per
100m\textsuperscript{2} were counted in 2006 and 2008 (PERSGA 2010)(Kotb
2010) and 8.9A±1.33 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2} (JREDS 2015), lower
than in the Indo-Pacific region (10 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2}
reef) and Indonesia (18 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2} reef). The
abundances in Egypt were lower (6.23A±0.69 fish per
100m\textsuperscript{2}) and in Saudi Arabia were higher (8.22A±0.36
fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2}) (PERSGA 2010)(Kotb 2010). The
abundance of Chaetodontid was reported as 11.75 fish per
100m\textsuperscript{2} reef in 5m depth and 10.40 fish per
100m\textsuperscript{2} reef in 1981 (Bouchon-Navaro
1981)({\textbf{???}}).

Sweetlips (\emph{Haemulidae}) were taken as an indicator for
overfishing, as they are one of the most popular fish species. In the
Indo-Pacific, \textless{}1 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2} were found,
in Indonesia around four fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2}. No sweetlips
were found during any surveys in Jordan. 0.64A±0.07 fish per
100m\textsuperscript{2} were found in Egypt and 1.09A±0.03 fish per
100m\textsuperscript{2} in Saudi Arabia (PERSGA 2010)(Kotb 2010).

Grouper above a 30cm length of any species serve as an indicator for
overfishing of all types. Jordan has very low values at 0.25A±0.12 fish
per 100m\textsuperscript{2}(PERSGA 2010) (Kotb 2010) in 2006 and 2008;
no grouper were found in the 2015 survey (JREDS 2015). This is in
contrast to Egypt with 0.75A±0.35 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2} and
Saudi Arabia with 1.03A±0.20 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2}. The
recorded abundance from Red Sea reefs during 1997-2001 (average:
1.15A±1.3 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2}) and from the Indo-Pacific
region was much higher (0.45A±0.98 fish per 100m\textsuperscript{2})
(PERSGA 2010) (Kotb 2010).

The results of the surveys suggest that the local reef fish populations
are heavily overfished. This is supported by the findings of the current
fisheries data collection, which shows that for the first time about
33\% of the fishermen come back from the sea without any catch.

Annual fish production in Jordan is also highly variable. Previous
research has shown that production in 1999 was 450 metric tons, while
production in 1998 comprised 120 metric tons (Kotb 2010). 2015 saw a
production of 80.5 metric tons, smaller than in previous years on
record. Previous studies also do not indicate the major presence of
Swordfish (Xiphiidae) in the Jordanian catch (Al-Zibdah, Khalaf, and
Odat 2006), yet currently, Xiphiidae make up 23.5\% of the catch weight.
Meanwhile, the share of tuna has dropped from 60.3\% in 1999/2000 to 52
in 2015 (Al-Zibdah, Khalaf, and Odat 2006).

